    "summary": "Diogenes of Sinope (c. 412–323 BC) was the most famous practitioner of Cynicism, a philosophical practice that rejected conventional social values — wealth, status, political power, and social propriety — in favor of radical self-sufficiency, virtue, and living according to nature, expressed through deliberately provocative behavior and reportedly living in a large ceramic jar.\n\nDiogenes was exiled from Sinope (possibly for defacing coins, literally or figuratively) and settled in Athens, where he studied with the Cynic founder Antisthenes before establishing his own notoriety. His anecdotes — carrying a lamp in daylight 'looking for an honest man,' telling Alexander the Great to stop blocking his sunlight, urinating on people who irritated him — made him a counter-cultural icon who challenged social conventions through action rather than argument. When asked what city he was from, he reportedly said 'I am a citizen of the world' (kosmopolites) — the first recorded use of the term 'cosmopolitan.' His philosophy rejected the need for civilization, government, or social institutions, advocating a life reduced to natural essentials. Cynicism influenced the Stoics ([[event:1195|Stoicism Founded]]), who admired Diogenes' self-sufficiency while moderating his social rejection, and his image of the philosopher who questions all conventional values remains a cultural touchstone.",
